.SH NAME
Notification.silent \- Notification: silent property
.SH SYNOPSIS
\f[B]Secure context:\f[R] This feature is available only in secure
contexts (HTTPS).
.PP
\f[B]Note:\f[R] This feature is available in Web Workers.
.PP
The \f[B]\f[CB]silent\f[B]\f[R] read\-only property of the
\f[CR]Notification\f[R] interface specifies whether the notification
should be silent, i.e., no sounds or vibrations should be issued
regardless of the device settings.
This is controlled via the \f[CR]silent\f[R] option of the
\f[CR]Notification()\f[R] constructor.
.SH VALUE
A boolean value or \f[CR]null\f[R].
If set to \f[CR]true\f[R], the notification is silent; if set to
\f[CR]null\f[R] (the default value), the device\[cq]s default settings
are respected.
.SH EXAMPLES
The following snippet fires a silent notification.
An \f[CR]options\f[R] object is created, and the notification is fired
in response to a button click using the \f[CR]Notification()\f[R]
constructor.
The code also includes rudimentary permissions handling, requesting
permission from the user to fire notifications if it has not already
been granted.
.IP
.EX
\f[B]const\f[R] btn = document.querySelector(\[dq]button\[dq]);

\f[B]const\f[R] options = {
  body: \[dq]No annoying pings or vibrations?\[dq],
  silent: \f[B]true\f[R],
};

\f[B]function\f[R] requestSilentNotification() {
  \f[B]const\f[R] n = \f[B]new\f[R] Notification(\[dq]Silent notification\[dq], options);
  console.log(n.silent); \f[I]// should return true\f[R]
}

btn.addEventListener(\[dq]click\[dq], () \f[B]=>\f[R] {
  \f[B]if\f[R] (Notification.permission === \[dq]granted\[dq]) {
    requestSilentNotification();
  } \f[B]else\f[R] {
    Notification.requestPermission().then((permission) \f[B]=>\f[R] {
      \f[B]if\f[R] (permission === \[dq]granted\[dq]) {
        requestSilentNotification();
      } \f[B]else\f[R] {
        console.log(\[dq]Notification permission was not granted\[dq]);
      }
    });
  }
});
